### Example 1.10: Free Fall with Air Resistance (Qualitative)

In reality, air resistance adds a velocity-dependent drag term. We can't solve it in closed form easily, but we can describe the terminal velocity `v_t = sqrt((2*m*g)/(ρ*C_d*A))`. For a skydiver (mass 70 kg, cross-section ~0.5 m², drag coefficient ~1, air density ~1.2 kg/m³), compute `v_t`.

```scheme
(define m 70)       ; kg
(define g 9.8)      ; m/s^2
(define rho 1.2)    ; kg/m^3
(define Cd 1.0)
(define A 0.5)      ; m^2

(define v-terminal 
  (sqrt (/ (* 2 m g) (* rho Cd A))))

(list 'terminal-velocity v-terminal 'm/s)
```

[VISUAL: Text `(terminal-velocity 47.9 m/s)` — about 107 mph.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


