## Topic 3: Simple Harmonic Motion and Oscillators

**History and uses:** The harmonic oscillator (a mass on a spring, or a pendulum for small angles) is the most important model in physics. Hooke's law (`F = -k*x`, 1660) describes springs. The differential equation `m*a = -k*x` leads to sinusoidal motion. Oscillators appear in clocks, musical instruments, electrical circuits (LC circuits), quantum mechanics (the quantum harmonic oscillator is exactly solvable), and signal processing (every waveform is a sum of sines via Fourier).

**What we'll cover:** We'll derive the period and frequency of a mass-spring system, plot its motion, compute total energy, and show how damping and driving forces affect it.

**Utility in Motoi:** The `phys/rlc-damping` verb analyzes the damping behavior of an electrical RLC circuit, which is mathematically identical to a damped mechanical oscillator.


### Example 3.1: Spring Period and Frequency

A mass `m` on a spring with constant `k` oscillates with period `T = 2π*sqrt(m/k)` and frequency `f = 1/T`.

```scheme
(define m 0.5)   ; kg
(define k 20)    ; N/m

(define omega (sqrt (/ k m)))  ; angular frequency rad/s
(define T (/ (* 2 (const/pi)) omega))
(define f (/ 1 T))

(list 'period T 'frequency f)
```

[VISUAL: Text `(period 0.99 frequency 1.01)` in seconds and Hz.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 3.2: Position vs. Time for SHM

`x(t) = A * cos(ω*t + φ)`. Plot position over two periods for amplitude `A = 0.1 m`, starting at maximum displacement (φ = 0).

```scheme
(define A 0.1)
(define omega 6.28)  ; rad/s (approx 2π)
(define phi 0)

(define T (/ (* 2 (const/pi)) omega))
(define times (map (lambda (i) (* 2 T (/ i 99))) (math/array 0 99)))

(define positions 
  (map (lambda (t)
         (geom/point t (* A (geom/cos (+ (* omega t) phi)))))
       times))

(plot/with
  (plot/line positions))
```

[VISUAL: Graphing-calculator Cartesian plot; horizontal = time (s), vertical = position (m); sinusoidal wave, amplitude 0.1 m, two complete cycles.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as Cartesian line plot. -->


### Example 3.3: Velocity vs. Time

Velocity is the derivative: `v(t) = -A*ω*sin(ω*t + φ)`.

```scheme
(define A 0.1)
(define omega 6.28)
(define phi 0)

(define T (/ (* 2 (const/pi)) omega))
(define times (map (lambda (i) (* 2 T (/ i 99))) (math/array 0 99)))

(define velocities 
  (map (lambda (t)
         (geom/point t (* (- A) omega (geom/sin (+ (* omega t) phi)))))
       times))

(plot/with
  (plot/line velocities))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot; velocity oscillates between ±0.628 m/s, 90° out of phase with position.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as line plot. -->


### Example 3.4: Total Energy (Constant)

For SHM, `E = (1/2)*k*A^2` (constant, alternating between kinetic and potential).

```scheme
(define k 20)
(define A 0.1)

(define E (* 0.5 k A A))

(list 'total-energy E 'Joules)
```

[VISUAL: Text `(total-energy 0.1 Joules)`.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 3.5: Energy at Arbitrary Time

At time `t`, `KE = (1/2)*m*v^2`, `PE = (1/2)*k*x^2`, and `KE + PE = E`.

```scheme
(define m 0.5)
(define k 20)
(define A 0.1)
(define omega (sqrt (/ k m)))
(define t 0.25)  ; seconds

(define x (* A (geom/cos (* omega t))))
(define v (* (- A) omega (geom/sin (* omega t))))

(define KE (* 0.5 m v v))
(define PE (* 0.5 k x x))
(define E-total (+ KE PE))

(list 'KE KE 'PE PE 'total E-total)
```

[VISUAL: Text `(KE 0.045 PE 0.055 total 0.1)` — sums to constant energy.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 3.6: Damped Harmonic Oscillator (Underdamped)

Add a damping force `F_d = -b*v`. The equation becomes `m*a = -k*x - b*v`, leading to exponentially decaying oscillations. The solution (underdamped) is `x(t) = A * exp(-γ*t) * cos(ω_d*t)`, where `γ = b/(2m)` and `ω_d = sqrt(ω0^2 - γ^2)`.

Plot the damped motion.

```scheme
(define m 0.5)
(define k 20)
(define b 0.5)  ; damping coefficient

(define omega0 (sqrt (/ k m)))
(define gamma (/ b (* 2 m)))
(define omega-d (sqrt (- (* omega0 omega0) (* gamma gamma))))

(define A 0.1)

(define times (map (lambda (i) (* 5 (/ i 99))) (math/array 0 99)))

(define damped-positions 
  (map (lambda (t)
         (geom/point t 
                     (* A (math/exp (* (- gamma) t)) 
                           (geom/cos (* omega-d t)))))
       times))

(plot/with
  (plot/line damped-positions))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot; sinusoidal oscillation with exponentially decaying envelope, amplitude shrinking over time.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as line plot. -->


### Example 3.7: RLC Circuit Damping

An electrical RLC circuit (resistor, inductor, capacitor in series) obeys the same equation as a damped oscillator. The `phys/rlc-damping` verb classifies the damping regime (underdamped, critically damped, overdamped).

```scheme
(define R 10)   ; ohms
(define L 0.1)  ; henries
(define C 1e-3) ; farads

(phys/rlc-damping R L C)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `\"underdamped\"` or `\"critically-damped\"` or `\"overdamped\"` depending on the values.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 3.8: Critically Damped Case

For critical damping, `γ = ω0`, so `b = 2*sqrt(k*m)`. The system returns to equilibrium without oscillating.

```scheme
(define m 0.5)
(define k 20)
(define b (* 2 (sqrt (* k m))))  ; critical damping

(define gamma (/ b (* 2 m)))
(define omega0 (sqrt (/ k m)))

(list 'gamma gamma 'omega0 omega0 'critically-damped? (< (abs (- gamma omega0)) 0.01))
```

[VISUAL: Text `(gamma 6.32 omega0 6.32 critically-damped? #t)`.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 3.9: Pendulum (Small Angle)

For small angles, a pendulum's motion is SHM with `ω = sqrt(g/L)`.

```scheme
(define g 9.8)
(define L 1)  ; meter

(define omega (sqrt (/ g L)))
(define T (/ (* 2 (const/pi)) omega))

(list 'period T 'seconds)
```

[VISUAL: Text `(period 2.01 seconds)` — the classic \"1-meter pendulum has a ~2-second period\".]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 3.10: Pendulum Energy (Exact, Not Small Angle)

For a pendulum with length `L`, mass `m`, and angle `θ` from vertical, `PE = m*g*L*(1 - cos(θ))`, `KE = (1/2)*m*L^2*(dθ/dt)^2`.

At release from `θ0 = 30°` with zero velocity, compute initial PE.

```scheme
(define m 1)
(define g 9.8)
(define L 1)
(define theta0-deg 30)
(define theta0-rad (geom/->radians theta0-deg))

(define PE0 (* m g L (- 1 (geom/cos theta0-rad))))

(list 'initial-PE PE0 'Joules)
```

[VISUAL: Text `(initial-PE 1.34 Joules)`.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


