## Topic 5: Waves and Fields — Continuous Systems

**History and uses:** Wave phenomena (sound, light, water waves) are described by partial differential equations (PDEs). The wave equation `∂²u/∂t² = c²*∂²u/∂x²` (d'Alembert, Euler, 1740s) models vibrating strings, sound in air, electromagnetic waves. Fourier's heat equation (1822) introduced the idea of separating variables and expanding in sines/cosines. Maxwell's equations (1865) unified electricity and magnetism as waves. Engineers use wave analysis for acoustics, optics, telecommunications, and structural vibrations.

**What we'll cover:** We'll compute wave speed, plot standing waves, introduce gradient/divergence/curl (the vector calculus operators), and show line/surface integrals.

**Utility in Motoi:** The `calc/gradient`, `calc/divergence`, `calc/curl`, `calc/line-integral`, and `calc/surface-integral` verbs let her work with vector fields (a gradient field is conservative, a curl-free field is irrotational, etc.).


### Example 5.1: Wave Speed on a String

The wave speed on a string under tension `T` with linear mass density `μ` is `c = sqrt(T/μ)`.

```scheme
(define T-tension 50)  ; Newtons
(define mu 0.01)       ; kg/m

(define c (sqrt (/ T-tension mu)))

(list 'wave-speed c 'm/s)
```

[VISUAL: Text `(wave-speed 70.7 m/s)`.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 5.2: Standing Wave on a String

A string of length `L` fixed at both ends has normal modes with wavelengths `λ_n = 2*L/n` and frequencies `f_n = n*c/(2*L)`. Plot the first three modes.

```scheme
(define L 1)   ; meter
(define c 70)  ; m/s

(define mode-1-wavelength (/ (* 2 L) 1))
(define mode-1-freq (/ c mode-1-wavelength))

(define mode-2-wavelength (/ (* 2 L) 2))
(define mode-2-freq (/ c mode-2-wavelength))

(list 'mode-1 (list 'wavelength mode-1-wavelength 'freq mode-1-freq)
      'mode-2 (list 'wavelength mode-2-wavelength 'freq mode-2-freq))
```

[VISUAL: Text `(mode-1 (wavelength 2 freq 35) mode-2 (wavelength 1 freq 70))`.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


### Example 5.3: Plot a Standing Wave Shape

The displacement of mode `n` is `u(x,t) = A*sin(n*π*x/L)*cos(ω_n*t)`. Plot the shape at `t=0` for the first mode.

```scheme
(define A 0.05)
(define L 1)
(define n 1)

(define xs (map (lambda (i) (/ i 99)) (math/array 0 99)))

(define shape-t0 
  (map (lambda (x)
         (geom/point x (* A (geom/sin (/ (* n (const/pi) x) L)))))
       xs))

(plot/with
  (plot/line shape-t0))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot; horizontal = position along string (0 to 1 m), vertical = displacement; sine curve, one hump.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as line plot. -->


### Example 5.4: Gradient of a Scalar Field

The gradient `∇f` points in the direction of steepest ascent. For `f(x,y) = x^2 + y^2`, `∇f = (2x, 2y)`.

The `calc/gradient` verb computes this numerically.

```scheme
(define f (lambda (p) 
            (let ((x (cadr (assoc 'x p)))
                  (y (cadr (assoc 'y p))))
              (+ (* x x) (* y y)))))

(define point (list (cons 'x 1) (cons 'y 2)))

(calc/gradient f point)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `(vec/make 2 4)` — the gradient at (1,2) is (2, 4).]

<!-- BUILD: run; display vector. -->


### Example 5.5: Gradient Field Plot

Plot the gradient vectors of `f(x,y) = x^2 + y^2` on a grid.

```scheme
(define f (lambda (p) 
            (let ((x (cadr (assoc 'x p)))
                  (y (cadr (assoc 'y p))))
              (+ (* x x) (* y y)))))

(define grid 
  (let ((xs '(-2 -1 0 1 2))
        (ys '(-2 -1 0 1 2)))
    (apply append 
           (map (lambda (x)
                  (map (lambda (y) (list (cons 'x x) (cons 'y y))) ys))
                xs))))

(define field 
  (map (lambda (p)
         (list p (calc/gradient f p)))
       grid))

(plot/with
  (plot/vector-field field))
```

[VISUAL: D3-over-canvas vector field; arrows radiating outward from the origin, longer as you move away.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as vector field plot. -->


### Example 5.6: Divergence of a Vector Field

The divergence `∇·F` measures the \"outflow\" of a field. For `F = (x, y)`, `∇·F = ∂x/∂x + ∂y/∂y = 1 + 1 = 2` everywhere.

The `calc/divergence` verb computes this.

```scheme
(define F (lambda (p)
            (let ((x (cadr (assoc 'x p)))
                  (y (cadr (assoc 'y p))))
              (vec/make x y))))

(define point (list (cons 'x 1) (cons 'y 2)))

(calc/divergence F point)
```

[VISUAL: Text `2` — the divergence is constant.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display number. -->


### Example 5.7: Curl of a Vector Field (2D)

In 2D, the curl (really the z-component of the 3D curl) measures rotation. For `F = (-y, x)` (a rotation field), `curl F = ∂x/∂x - ∂(-y)/∂y = 0 - (-1) = 1`? No: `∂F_y/∂x - ∂F_x/∂y = ∂x/∂x - ∂(-y)/∂y = 1 - 1 = 0`? Let's recompute:

`F = (-y, x)`, so `F_x = -y`, `F_y = x`.  
`∂F_y/∂x = 1`, `∂F_x/∂y = -1`.  
`curl_z = ∂F_y/∂x - ∂F_x/∂y = 1 - (-1) = 2`.

The `calc/curl` verb (in 2D returns a scalar, in 3D a vector).

```scheme
(define F (lambda (p)
            (let ((x (cadr (assoc 'x p)))
                  (y (cadr (assoc 'y p))))
              (vec/make (- y) x))))

(define point (list (cons 'x 1) (cons 'y 2)))

(calc/curl F point)
```

[VISUAL: Text `2` — the curl at any point of a rotation field.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display number. -->


### Example 5.8: Conservative Field (Gradient Field)

A field `F` is conservative if `F = ∇φ` for some potential `φ`. Then `curl F = 0` (in 2D). Check for `F = (2x, 2y)` (the gradient of `x^2 + y^2`).

```scheme
(define F (lambda (p)
            (let ((x (cadr (assoc 'x p)))
                  (y (cadr (assoc 'y p))))
              (vec/make (* 2 x) (* 2 y)))))

(define point (list (cons 'x 1) (cons 'y 2)))

(calc/curl F point)
```

[VISUAL: Text `0` — curl is zero, confirming conservative.]

<!-- BUILD: run; display number. -->


### Example 5.9: Line Integral of a Vector Field

The work done by force `F` along a curve `C` is `∫_C F·dr`. The `calc/line-integral` verb computes this.

For `F = (y, x)` along the straight line from (0,0) to (1,1):

```scheme
(define F (lambda (p)
            (let ((x (cadr (assoc 'x p)))
                  (y (cadr (assoc 'y p))))
              (vec/make y x))))

(define curve 
  (lambda (t) 
    (list (cons 'x t) (cons 'y t))))  ; parametric: x=t, y=t, 0≤t≤1

(calc/line-integral F curve 0 1)
```

[VISUAL: Text output the numerical value of the integral (should be 1).]

<!-- BUILD: run; display number. -->


### Example 5.10: Surface Integral (Flux)

The flux of a field `F` through a surface `S` is `∫∫_S F·n dA`. For a flat surface in the xy-plane with `F = (0, 0, z)` and `n = (0,0,1)`, the flux is the integral of the z-component.

The `calc/surface-integral` verb handles this.

```scheme
(define F (lambda (p)
            (let ((x (cadr (assoc 'x p)))
                  (y (cadr (assoc 'y p)))
                  (z (cadr (assoc 'z p))))
              (vec/make 0 0 z))))

(define surface 
  (lambda (u v) 
    (list (cons 'x u) (cons 'y v) (cons 'z 0))))  ; z=0 plane, 0≤u,v≤1

(calc/surface-integral F surface 0 1 0 1)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `0` (since z=0 everywhere on the surface).]

<!-- BUILD: run; display number. -->


