## Topic 6: N-Body Dynamics and Orbits

**History and uses:** The N-body problem (predicting the motion of N gravitationally interacting masses) has no closed-form solution for N>2 (Poincaré proved it's non-integrable in the 1890s). Numerical integrators (Runge-Kutta, symplectic methods) are essential. Orbital mechanics (Kepler's laws, 1609–1619) describes planetary motion; NASA uses numerical N-body codes for mission design.

**What we'll cover:** We'll use the `phys/nbody` verb to simulate a simple two-body orbit and a three-body system.

**Utility in Motoi:** The `phys/nbody` integrator lets her simulate gravitational (or electrostatic) systems on the canvas.


### Example 6.1: Two-Body Circular Orbit (Earth-Moon Simplification)

Place Earth at the origin, Moon in circular orbit. We'll use reduced units for simplicity.

```scheme
;; Masses (arbitrary units)
(define m-earth 100)
(define m-moon 1)

;; Initial conditions: Moon at (10, 0) with velocity (0, v-circ)
;; For circular orbit: v = sqrt(G*M/r)
(define G 1)  ; set G=1 for convenience
(define r 10)
(define v-circ (sqrt (/ (* G m-earth) r)))

(define bodies 
  (list 
    (list 'mass m-earth 'pos (vec/make 0 0) 'vel (vec/make 0 0))
    (list 'mass m-moon  'pos (vec/make r 0) 'vel (vec/make 0 v-circ))))

;; Evolve for 100 time units, 200 steps
(define trajectory (phys/nbody bodies 100 200))

;; Extract Moon's path
(define moon-path 
  (map (lambda (state)
         (let ((moon-pos (cadr (assoc 'pos (cadr state)))))
           (geom/point (vec/ref moon-pos 0) (vec/ref moon-pos 1))))
       trajectory))

(plot/with
  (plot/line moon-path))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot; circular (or near-circular) orbit around the origin.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as line plot. The exact API of phys/nbody (returns list of states) must match the wired verb. -->


### Example 6.2: Elliptical Orbit

Increase the Moon's initial velocity slightly to get an ellipse.

```scheme
(define m-earth 100)
(define m-moon 1)
(define G 1)
(define r 10)
(define v-circ (sqrt (/ (* G m-earth) r)))
(define v-ellipse (* 1.2 v-circ))  ; 20% faster

(define bodies 
  (list 
    (list 'mass m-earth 'pos (vec/make 0 0) 'vel (vec/make 0 0))
    (list 'mass m-moon  'pos (vec/make r 0) 'vel (vec/make 0 v-ellipse))))

(define trajectory (phys/nbody bodies 100 200))

(define moon-path 
  (map (lambda (state)
         (let ((moon-pos (cadr (assoc 'pos (cadr state)))))
           (geom/point (vec/ref moon-pos 0) (vec/ref moon-pos 1))))
       trajectory))

(plot/with
  (plot/line moon-path))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot; elliptical orbit with Earth at one focus.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as line plot. -->


### Example 6.3: Three-Body Figure-Eight (Simplified)

The famous figure-eight solution (discovered numerically by Moore, 1993, and proved by Chenciner & Montgomery, 2000) requires precise initial conditions. We'll set up a simpler three-body system and watch the chaos.

```scheme
(define bodies 
  (list 
    (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make -1 0)  'vel (vec/make 0 0.5))
    (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make 1 0)   'vel (vec/make 0 -0.5))
    (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make 0 1.5) 'vel (vec/make -0.5 0))))

(define trajectory (phys/nbody bodies 50 300))

;; Extract paths for each body
(define path-0 
  (map (lambda (state)
         (let ((pos (cadr (assoc 'pos (car state)))))
           (geom/point (vec/ref pos 0) (vec/ref pos 1))))
       trajectory))

(define path-1 
  (map (lambda (state)
         (let ((pos (cadr (assoc 'pos (cadr state)))))
           (geom/point (vec/ref pos 0) (vec/ref pos 1))))
       trajectory))

(define path-2 
  (map (lambda (state)
         (let ((pos (cadr (assoc 'pos (caddr state)))))
           (geom/point (vec/ref pos 0) (vec/ref pos 1))))
       trajectory))

(plot/with
  (plot/line path-0)
  (plot/line path-1)
  (plot/line path-2))
```

[VISUAL: Cartesian plot with three intertwined paths; chaotic, sensitive to initial conditions.]

<!-- BUILD: run; render as multi-line plot. -->


### Example 6.4: Energy Conservation Check

For an isolated N-body system, total energy `E = KE + PE` is conserved. Compute `E` at the start and end of the simulation.

```scheme
(define G 1)

(define compute-energy 
  (lambda (state)
    (let* ((bodies state)
           (KE (apply + 
                      (map (lambda (b)
                             (let ((m (cadr (assoc 'mass b)))
                                   (v (cadr (assoc 'vel b))))
                               (* 0.5 m (vec/dot v v))))
                           bodies)))
           (PE 
             (apply + 
                    (apply append 
                           (map (lambda (i)
                                  (map (lambda (j)
                                         (if (< i j)
                                             (let* ((bi (list-ref bodies i))
                                                    (bj (list-ref bodies j))
                                                    (mi (cadr (assoc 'mass bi)))
                                                    (mj (cadr (assoc 'mass bj)))
                                                    (ri (cadr (assoc 'pos bi)))
                                                    (rj (cadr (assoc 'pos bj)))
                                                    (dr (vec/- rj ri))
                                                    (r (vec/norm dr)))
                                               (/ (* (- G) mi mj) r))
                                             0))
                                       (math/array 0 (- (length bodies) 1))))
                                (math/array 0 (- (length bodies) 1)))))))
      (+ KE PE))))

;; Initial energy
(define E0 (compute-energy (list 
                             (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make -1 0) 'vel (vec/make 0 0.5))
                             (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make 1 0)  'vel (vec/make 0 -0.5))
                             (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make 0 1.5) 'vel (vec/make -0.5 0)))))

;; Run simulation
(define trajectory (phys/nbody 
                     (list 
                       (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make -1 0) 'vel (vec/make 0 0.5))
                       (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make 1 0)  'vel (vec/make 0 -0.5))
                       (list 'mass 1 'pos (vec/make 0 1.5) 'vel (vec/make -0.5 0)))
                     50 300))

(define E-final (compute-energy (car (reverse trajectory))))

(list 'E-initial E0 'E-final E-final 'drift (abs (- E-final E0)))
```

[VISUAL: Text `(E-initial <value> E-final <value> drift <small number>)` — energy should be nearly conserved (small drift from numerical error).]

<!-- BUILD: run; display text. -->


